Obesity Prediction

by Federico Gerardi

Download Dataset

In this section, we download the dataset and split it into training and testing sets.

In this section we download the dataset and we separate train and test sets

In[]:
import numpy as np # Operations for linear algebra
import math
import pandas as pd # Data processing and reading CSV files using Pandas (e.g., pd.read_csv)
from sklearn import metrics
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns


url='https://drive.google.com/file/d/12dUeEO_rkButPD79pOteFoSSeuIBg5qt/view?usp=drive_link'
file_id=url.split('/')[-2]
dwn_url='https://drive.google.com/uc?id=' + file_id
dataset = pd.read_csv(dwn_url)
In[]:
TRAIN_TEST_SPLIT_PERCENTAGE = 0.9
dataset_training = dataset[:int(len(dataset) * TRAIN_TEST_SPLIT_PERCENTAGE)]
dataset_test = dataset[int(len(dataset) * TRAIN_TEST_SPLIT_PERCENTAGE):]

Linear Regression using the Normal Equation

This section utilizes the normal equation to create a predictive model.

Data manipulation

In this code block we are manipulating the dataset, removing all the possible strings and replacing them with numbers.

In[]:
gender_map = {"Male": 0, "Female": 1}

dataset.Gender.replace(gender_map, inplace=True)

y_n_map = {"yes": 1, "no": 0}

dataset.family_history_with_overweight.replace(y_n_map, inplace=True)

dataset.FAVC.replace(y_n_map, inplace=True)
dataset.SMOKE.replace(y_n_map, inplace=True)
dataset.SCC.replace(y_n_map, inplace=True)

times_map = {"no": 0, "Sometimes": 1, "Frequently": 2, "Always": 3}

dataset.CAEC.replace(times_map, inplace=True)
dataset.CALC.replace(times_map, inplace=True)

trans_map = {"Public_Transportation": 3, "Walking": 0, "Automobile": 4, "Motorbike": 2, "Bike": 1}

dataset.MTRANS.replace(trans_map, inplace=True)

obesity_map = {"Insufficient_Weight": 0, "Normal_Weight": 1, "Overweight_Level_I": 2, "Overweight_Level_II": 3, "Obesity_Type_I": 4, "Obesity_Type_II": 5, "Obesity_Type_III": 6}

dataset.NObeyesdad.replace(obesity_map, inplace=True)

Let's separate training set and test set with a 90% proportion.

Also we shuffle data.

In[]:
sh_dataset = dataset.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)  # Shuffle the dataset to randomize order
dataset_training = sh_dataset[:int(len(dataset) * TRAIN_TEST_SPLIT_PERCENTAGE)]
dataset_test = sh_dataset[int(len(dataset) * TRAIN_TEST_SPLIT_PERCENTAGE):]

We build the x matrix and y vector of training and test

X matrix has the bias in the first column and contains the whole dataset except the weight one.

Y vector contains only the weight column.

In[]:
# Training
y = dataset_training.Weight
y = y.to_numpy()

x = dataset_training.copy()
del x["Weight"]
x = x.to_numpy()

bias = np.ones(shape=(len(x), 1))
x = np.concatenate((bias, x), axis=1)

# Test
y_test = dataset_test.Weight.reset_index(drop=True)
x_test = dataset_test.copy()
del x_test["Weight"]
x_test = x_test.to_numpy()
bias = np.ones(shape=(len(x_test), 1))
x_test = np.concatenate((bias, x_test), axis=1)

Training

Calculation of the pseudoinverse.

In[]:
c = np.linalg.pinv(x)@y

Compare the value with the Sklearn one

Testing

In[]:
model = LinearRegression()

model.fit(x, y)

y_sk = model.predict(x_test)

print(f"Our MSE: {metrics.mean_squared_error(x_test@c, y_test)}\t RMSE: {np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(x_test@c, y_test))}\t MAE: {metrics.mean_absolute_error(x_test@c, y_test)}")
print(f"Sklearn MSE: {metrics.mean_squared_error(y_sk, y_test)}\t RMSE: {np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_sk, y_test))}\t MAE: {metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_sk, y_test)}")

Our MSE: 26.014091235970646	 RMSE: 5.100401085794199	 MAE: 3.9527638148680007
Sklearn MSE: 26.014091235970586	 RMSE: 5.100401085794194	 MAE: 3.952763814868014

sh_dataset = dataset.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)  # Shuffle the dataset to randomize order
dataset_training = sh_dataset[:int(len(dataset) * TRAIN_TEST_SPLIT_PERCENTAGE)]
dataset_test = sh_dataset[int(len(dataset) * TRAIN_TEST_SPLIT_PERCENTAGE):]

# Training
y = dataset_training.Weight
y = y.to_numpy()

x = dataset_training.copy()
del x["Weight"]
x = x.to_numpy()

bias = np.ones(shape=(len(x), 1))
x = np.concatenate((bias, x), axis=1)

# Test
y_test = dataset_test.Weight.reset_index(drop=True)
x_test = dataset_test.copy()
del x_test["Weight"]
x_test = x_test.to_numpy()
bias = np.ones(shape=(len(x_test), 1))
x_test = np.concatenate((bias, x_test), axis=1)

Function definition

Gradient descent to find the minimum of the MSE

In[]:
def linear_regression_gradient_descent(x, y, alpha, epochs):
  _, N = np.shape(x)

  c = np.random.rand(N,)

  for i in range(epochs):
    x_c = (x @ c)
    grad = (x.T @ (x_c - y)) / N

    c = c - alpha * grad

    print(f"epoch: {i}\t error: {metrics.mean_squared_error(x@c, y)}")

  return c

2 Hyperparameters:

  • Alpha
  • Epochs

Training

GridSearch with some hyperparameters.

In[]:
hyperparameters = [
    {
        'alpha': 10e-6,
        'epochs': 10000
    },
    {
        'alpha': 10e-6,
        'epochs': 100000
    },
    {
        'alpha': 10e-6,
        'epochs': 100
    }
]

c_list = list()

for params in hyperparameters:
  c = linear_regression_gradient_descent(x, y, params['alpha'], params['epochs'])
  c_list.append(c)

Testing

Test models, comparing them with sklearn ones.

In[]:
model = LinearRegression()

model.fit(x, y)

y_sk = model.predict(x_test)


min_mse = [100000000, 0]

for i in range(len(hyperparameters)):
  mse = metrics.mean_squared_error(x_test@c_list[i], y_test)
  print(f"C[{i}] MSE: {mse}\t RMSE: {np.sqrt(mse)}\t MAE: {metrics.mean_absolute_error(x_test@c_list[i], y_test)}")
  if mse < min_mse[0]:
    min_mse = [mse, i]

print(f'The best model is the #{min_mse[1]} using alpha={hyperparameters[min_mse[1]]["alpha"]} and epochs={hyperparameters[min_mse[1]]["epochs"]} with MSE: {min_mse[0]}')
print(f"Sklearn MSE: {metrics.mean_squared_error(y_sk, y_test)}\t RMSE: {np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_sk, y_test))}\t MAE: {metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_sk, y_test)}")

dataset

sh_dataset = dataset.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)  # Shuffle the dataset to randomize order
dataset_training = sh_dataset[:int(len(dataset) * TRAIN_TEST_SPLIT_PERCENTAGE)]
dataset_test = sh_dataset[int(len(dataset) * TRAIN_TEST_SPLIT_PERCENTAGE):]

# Training
y = dataset_training.Weight
y = y.to_numpy()

x = dataset_training.copy()
del x["Weight"]
x = x.to_numpy()

bias = np.ones(shape=(len(x), 1))
x = np.concatenate((bias, x), axis=1)

# Test
y_test = dataset_test.Weight.reset_index(drop=True)
x_test = dataset_test.copy()
del x_test["Weight"]
x_test = x_test.to_numpy()
bias = np.ones(shape=(len(x_test), 1))
x_test = np.concatenate((bias, x_test), axis=1)

Function Definition

Same but with mini-batches

In[]:
def linear_regression_sgd(x, y, alpha, batch_size, epochs):
  _, N = np.shape(x)

  c = np.random.rand(N,)

  epochs = epochs * batch_size

  x_split = np.array_split(x, batch_size)
  y_split = np.array_split(y, batch_size)

  for i in range(epochs):
    x_c = (x_split[i % batch_size] @ c)
    grad = (x_split[i % batch_size].T @ (x_c - y_split[i % batch_size])) / N

    c = c - alpha * grad

    if i % batch_size == 0:
      print(f"epoch: {i/batch_size}\t error: {metrics.mean_squared_error(x@c, y)}")


  return c

3 hyperparameters:

  • alpha
  • mini batch size
  • epoches

Training

In[]:
hyperparameters = [
    {
        'alpha': 10e-6,
        'batch_size': 9,
        'epochs': 500
    },
    {
        'alpha': 10e-6,
        'batch_size': 18,
        'epochs': 100
    },
    {
        'alpha': 10e-6,
        'batch_size': 20,
        'epochs': 100
    }
]

c_list = list()

for params in hyperparameters:
  c = linear_regression_sgd(x, y, params['alpha'], params['batch_size'], params['epochs'])
  c_list.append(c)

dataset.NObeyesdad.replace(obesity_map, inplace=True)

dataset['Height'] = dataset['Height'].apply(lambda x : x * 10)

dataset = dataset.astype({"Age": "int", "Height": "int", "Weight": "int", "FCVC": "int", "NCP": "int", "CH2O": "int", "FAF": "int", "TUE": "int"})

Class definition

Two classes:

  • Attribute: Contains the name of the attribute and all its possible values

  • DecisionTree: The Tree

In[]:
class Attribute:
  name = str()
  values = []
  def __init__(self, name, values):
    self.name = name
    self.values = values  # []

  def __str__(self):
    return self.name


class DecisionTree:
  attribute = None
  subtree = []
  def __init__(self, attribute):
    self.attribute = attribute  # Attribute
    self.subtrees = []  # [(DecisionTree, value)]


  def add_sub(self, subtree):
    self.subtrees.append(subtree)

Useful functions

In[]:
def get_examples_set(examples, attribute, value):
  result = []

  for e in examples:
    if e[attribute] == value:
      result.append(e)

  return result

def remove_attribute_from_set(attributes, A):
  result = attributes.copy()
  result.remove(A)
  return result


def count_yes(examples):
  count = 0
  for e in examples:
    if e[len(e)-1]:
      count += 1

  return count

def count_no(examples):
  count = 0

  for e in examples:
    if not e[len(e)-1]:
      count += 1

  return count

def plurality_value(examples, attributes):
  return int(count_yes(examples) > count_no(examples))


def same_classification(examples):
  return int(count_yes(examples) == 0 or count_no(examples) == 0)


def B(q):
  if q == 0:
    return 0
  return -(q*np.log2(q)+(1-q)*np.log2(1-q))

def Remainder(A, index_a, examples):
  ret = 0
  for v in A.values:
    exs = get_examples_set(examples, index_a, v)
    if len(exs) > 2:
      ret += ((count_yes(exs) + count_no(exs))/(len(examples)))*B(count_yes(exs)/(len(examples)))

  return ret

def max_importance(attributes, examples):
  max_i = 0
  max_A = None
  for a in attributes:
    i = B(count_yes(examples)/(len(examples))) - Remainder(a, attributes.index(a), examples)
    if i > max_i:
      max_i = i
      max_A = a

  return max_A

Gready Algorithm implemented

In[]:
def learn_decision_tree (examples, attributes, parent_examples):
  if len(examples) == 0:
    return plurality_value(parent_examples, attributes)
  elif same_classification(examples):
    return examples[0][-1]
  elif len(attributes) == 0:
    return plurality_value(examples, attributes)
  else:
    A = max_importance(attributes, examples)
    tree = DecisionTree(A)
    for v in A.values:
      exs = get_examples_set(examples, attributes.index(A), v)
      subtree = learn_decision_tree(exs, remove_attribute_from_set(attributes, A), examples)
      tree.add_sub((subtree, v))

  return tree

    Attribute("CAEC", [0, 1, 2, 3]),
    Attribute("SMOKE", [0, 1]),
    Attribute("CH2O", [1, 2, 3]),
    Attribute("SCC", [0, 1]),
    Attribute("FAF", [0, 1, 2, 3]),
    Attribute("TUE", [0, 1, 2]),
    Attribute("CALC", [0, 1, 2, 3]),
    Attribute("MTRANS", [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]),
    Attribute("NObeyesdad", [0, 1])
]


dec_tree = learn_decision_tree(dataset_training.to_numpy(), attribute_array, None)



def print_decision_tree(tree, h):
  if type(tree[0]) != DecisionTree:
    if type(tree[0]) == np.int64 or type(tree[0]) == int:
      print("  " * h + f"|_{tree[1]}_", tree[0])
      return


  print("  " * h + f"|_{tree[1]}_", tree[0].attribute.name)

  for sub in tree[0].subtrees:
    print_decision_tree(sub, h+1)



def predict_decision_tree(x, tree, attribute_array):
  for sub in tree[0].subtrees:

    if x[attribute_array.index(tree[0].attribute)] == sub[1]:

      if type(sub[0]) == DecisionTree:
        return predict_decision_tree(x, sub, attribute_array)
      else:
        return sub[0]

y_test = np.zeros((dataset_test.shape[0]))
i = 0
for x in dataset_test.to_numpy():

  y_test[i] = x[-1]
  i += 1

print(f"False negatives: {cm.sum(axis=1) - np.diag(cm)}")

y_n_map = {"yes": 1, "no": 0}

dataset.family_history_with_overweight.replace(y_n_map, inplace=True)

dataset.FAVC.replace(y_n_map, inplace=True)
dataset.SMOKE.replace(y_n_map, inplace=True)
dataset.SCC.replace(y_n_map, inplace=True)

times_map = {"no": 0, "Sometimes": 1, "Frequently": 2, "Always": 3}

dataset.CAEC.replace(times_map, inplace=True)
dataset.CALC.replace(times_map, inplace=True)

trans_map = {"Public_Transportation": 3, "Walking": 0, "Automobile": 4, "Motorbike": 2, "Bike": 1}

dataset.MTRANS.replace(trans_map, inplace=True)

obesity_map = {"Insufficient_Weight": 0, "Normal_Weight": 0, "Overweight_Level_I": 0, "Overweight_Level_II": 0, "Obesity_Type_I": 1, "Obesity_Type_II": 1, "Obesity_Type_III": 1}

dataset.NObeyesdad.replace(obesity_map, inplace=True)

dataset['Height'] = dataset['Height'].apply(lambda x : x * 10)

dataset = dataset.astype({"Age": "int", "Height": "int", "Weight": "int", "FCVC": "int", "NCP": "int", "CH2O": "int", "FAF": "int", "TUE": "int"})

sh_dataset = dataset.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)  # Shuffle the dataset to randomize order
dataset_training = sh_dataset[:int(len(dataset) * TRAIN_TEST_SPLIT_PERCENTAGE)]
dataset_test = sh_dataset[int(len(dataset) * TRAIN_TEST_SPLIT_PERCENTAGE):]

Function Definition

In[]:
def logistic_regression_loss(y, y_pred):
  epsilon = 1e-15
  y_pred = np.clip(y_pred, epsilon, 1 - epsilon)

  sum = 0
  for i in range(len(y)):
    sum += (y[i]*np.log2(y_pred[i])) + ((1-y[i])*np.log2(1-y_pred[i]))

  return -(1/len(y))*sum

def logistic_predict(x, c):
  z = x@c
  z = 1/(1+np.exp(-z))
  return np.where(z >= 0.5, 1, 0)

def logistic_regression(x, y, alpha, batch_size, epochs):
  _, N = np.shape(x)

  c = np.random.rand(N,)

  epochs = epochs * batch_size

  x_split = np.array_split(x, batch_size)
  y_split = np.array_split(y, batch_size)

  for i in range(epochs):
    z = x_split[i % batch_size]@c
    logistic = 1/(1+np.exp(-z))
    grad = (logistic - y_split[i % batch_size])@x_split[i % batch_size]

    c = c - alpha * grad

    if i % batch_size == 0:
      print(f"epoch: {int(i/batch_size)}\t error {logistic_regression_loss(y, logistic_predict(x, c))}")

  return c

Training

for params in hyperparameters:
  c = logistic_regression(x, y, params['alpha'], params['batch_size'], params['epochs'])
  c_list.append(c)

  plt.ylabel('Precision')

  plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
  plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
  plt.title('ROC Curve')

nobes = dataset.NObeyesdad.copy()
del dataset["NObeyesdad"]

dataset_normalized = pd.concat([dataset_normalized, nobes], axis=1)

sh_dataset = dataset_normalized.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)  # Shuffle the dataset to randomize order
dataset_training = sh_dataset[:int(len(dataset) * TRAIN_TEST_SPLIT_PERCENTAGE)]
dataset_test = sh_dataset[int(len(dataset) * TRAIN_TEST_SPLIT_PERCENTAGE):]

Function Definition

Differents distances

In[]:
def euclidea(x, y):
  return np.linalg.norm(x - y)

def manhattan(x, y):
  return np.sum(np.abs(x - y))

def cosine(x, y):
  return np.dot(x, y)/(np.linalg.norm(x) + np.linalg.norm(y))


def distance(x, y, p='euclidean'):
  if p == 'euclidean':
      return np.linalg.norm(x - y)
  elif p == 'manhattan':
      return np.sum(np.abs(x - y))
  elif p == 'cosine':
      return np.dot(x, y) / (np.linalg.norm(x) * np.linalg.norm(y))
  else:
      return np.sum(np.abs(x - y) ** p) ** (1/p)

Predict function

In[]:
def most_common(lst):
    return max(set(lst), key=lst.count)

def predict_nn(x_test, x, y, K, p):
  mega_list = []

  for i in range(len(x)):
    dist = distance(x_test, x[i], p) # np.linalg.norm(x_test-x[i])
    mega_list.append((dist, y[i]))


  mega_list.sort()

  min_list = []

  for i in range(K):
    min_list.append(mega_list[i][1])

  return most_common(min_list)

def accuracy_knn(x_test, y_test, x, y, K, p):
  win = 0
  for i in range(len(x_test)):
    y_pred = predict_nn(x_test[i], x, y, K, p)
    if y_pred == y_test[i]:
      win += 1

  return win/len(x_test)

Class definition and functions

Activation function

In[]:
def sigmoid(x):
  return 1/(1+np.exp(-x))

def sigmoid_derivative(x):
  return x * (1 - x)

def relu(x):
  return np.maximum(0, x, dtype='float64')

def relu_derivative(dA, Z):
  dZ = np.array(dA, copy=True)
  dZ[Z <= 0] = 0
  return dZ

def threshold(z, value):
  ris = np.copy(z)
  ris[ris >= value] = 1
  ris[ris < value] = 0
  return ris

Neural Network Class

In[]:
class Layer:
  def __init__(self, nodes, activation=relu, derivative=relu_derivative):
    self.nodes = nodes
    self.activation = activation
    self.derivative = derivative


class NeuralNetwork:
  def __init__(self, layers):
    self.layers = layers    # [Layer(in, activation, derivative), Layer(h1, activation, derivative), Layer(h2, activation, derivative), ..., Layer(out, activation, derivative)]
    self.weights = list()   
    self.biases = list()    
    self.Z_list = list()   
    self.A_list = list()    
    self.plot_list = list() 

    self.init_weights()



  def init_weights(self):
      for i in range(len(self.layers) - 1):
        input_layer = self.layers[i].nodes    
        output_layer = self.layers[i+1].nodes 

        std_dev = np.sqrt(2.0 / float(input_layer)) 

        weight = np.random.randn(output_layer, input_layer) * std_dev  
        bias = np.zeros((output_layer, 1)) 
        self.weights.append(weight)
        self.biases.append(bias)


  def forward_propagation(self, x):
    A = np.asmatrix(np.copy(x), dtype='float64').T

    Z_tmp = list()
    A_tmp = [A]

    for i in range(len(self.layers)-1):
      Z = self.weights[i] @ A + self.biases[i]  

      A = self.layers[i].activation(Z) 

      A_tmp.append(A)
      Z_tmp.append(Z)

    self.Z_list = Z_tmp
    self.A_list = A_tmp

  def back_propagation(self, y_pred, y):

    dW = list()
    dB = list()


    dA_prev = (y_pred - y) 

    for i in reversed(range(len(self.layers)-1)):

        dA_curr = dA_prev

        A_prev = self.A_list[i]
        Z_curr = self.Z_list[i]
        W_curr = self.weights[i]

        dZ_curr = self.layers[i].derivative(dA_curr, Z_curr)

        m = A_prev.shape[1]

        dW_curr = (dZ_curr @ A_prev.T) / m
        dB_curr = np.sum(dZ_curr) / m
        dA_prev = W_curr.T @ dZ_curr

        dW.insert(0, dW_curr)
        dB.insert(0, dB_curr)

    return dW, dB

  def train(self, x_train, y_train, lr, epochs):

    loss_list = list()

    epoch = 0
    while epoch < epochs:

      loss = 0

      dW_list = list()
      dB_list = list()

      for x, y in zip(x_train, y_train):

        self.forward_propagation(x)   
        y_pred = self.A_list[-1]     

        loss += np.power((y_pred - y), 2) / 2 

        dW, dB = self.back_propagation(y_pred, y) 

        dW_list.append(dW)
        dB_list.append(dB)

        for i in range(len(self.layers)-1):

          self.weights[i] = self.weights[i] - lr * dW[i]
          self.biases[i] = self.biases[i] -  lr * dB[i]

      loss /= x_train.shape[0] 


      loss_list.append(int(loss.item()))

      if epoch == 5:
        loss_avg = int(sum(loss_list)/len(loss_list))
        if loss_avg == int(loss_list[0]):
          print("RESTART")
          epoch = 0
          self.weights = []
          self.init_weights()
          continue

      print(f'Epoch {epoch+1}, Loss: {loss.item()}') 
      self.plot_list.append((epoch, loss.item()))    

      epoch += 1


  def predict_one(self, x):
    self.forward_propagation(x)
    return float(self.A_list[-1].item())

  def predict_matrix(self, x_test):
    y_pred = list()

    for x in x_test:
      y_pred.append(self.predict_one(x))

    return np.array(y_pred)

Testing

In[]:
min_mse = [100000000, 0]

for i in range(len(nns)):
  y_pred = nns[i].predict_matrix(x_test)
  mse = metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
  print(f"NN[{i}]:  MSE: {mse}\t RMSE: {np.sqrt(mse)}\t MAE: {metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)}")
  if mse < min_mse[0]:
    min_mse = [mse, i]

print(f'The best Neural Network is is the #{min_mse[1]} using lr={hyperparameters[min_mse[1]]["lr"]} and epochs={hyperparameters[min_mse[1]]["epochs"]} and layers={[layer.nodes for layer in hyperparameters[min_mse[1]]["layers"]]} with MSE: {min_mse[0]}')

Conclusions

Linear regression

The best linear regression model is the normal equation. For two reasons:

  • The speed of computation is almost zero
    Since there are few features, computing the Moore-Penrose inverse matrix does not require much of resources
  • The MSE is identical to Sklearn's.

Models using the gradient descent technique take much longer to achieve minimal MSE advantage. Advantage that is not worth the waste of resources and time that has to be made to achieve it. The same argument applies to the neural network. Better results than gradient descent but after hours of training. We could have better results with more complex neural networks and after many hours of training, but we don't have enough data to do networks with so many layers and so many nodes.

Classification.

The best classification model is logistic regression. This is because with very few epochs you can get very high accuracy and instant predict. The learn decision tree has a very high risk of overfitting and a lower accuracy than logistic regression, but with the advantage of almost immediate tree construction. KNN has very good accuracy with K=2 and manhattan distance (competitive accuracy compared to logistic regression), but it takes time to compute a predict. However, it must be considered that KNN gives a very important advantage, which is multiclass classification, something that logistic, can't do.
